    • Field Detail

      • INVALID_MAGNITUDE

        public static final int INVALID_MAGNITUDE
        Constant that holds the magnitude of a planet or satellite when it is fully eclipsed/occulted.
        See Also:
        Constant Field Values

      • rightAscension

        public double rightAscension
        Right Ascension in radians. It is measured respect the true or mean equinox of the epoch selected in the ephemeris object. For positions calculated for an observer located in the surface of a planet different from the Earth, the reference RA = 0 is taken as the meridian containing the Earth's north pole at J2000. This criteria is not the same as the one used by JPL.

      • declination

        public double declination
        Declination in radians. It is measured respect the equator of the reference body, usually the Earth.

      • distance

        public double distance
        Distance to the observer in Astronomical Units. As a general rule, distance is calculated as 'apparent', which means that is referred to the instant light seen by the observer for a given calculation time, and not the true distance the body has at that time (that cannot be 'seen' due to its distance).

      • angularRadius

        public float angularRadius
        Angular radius in radians.

      • magnitude

        public float magnitude
        Apparent magnitude, corrected for extinction if the corresponding flag is enabled in the configuration class. This magnitude maybe not accurate for calculations done from outside the Earth.

      • distanceFromSun

        public double distanceFromSun
        Distance from the Sun in Astronomical Units. As a general rule, it is the distance that the planet had to the Sun when it emitted the light that reaches the observer at a given calculation time ('apparent', not the true geometric distance), since ephemerides are usually apparent, not geometric. Note that in certain methods (in fact, all of them except JPL ephemerides) the Sun is incorrectly assumed to be at the Solar System Barycenter (SSB), and this value is the distance to SSB, not to the Sun itsef.

      • elongation

        public float elongation
        Elongation in radians.

      • phaseAngle

        public float phaseAngle
        Phase angle in radians. It can be negative if the ecliptic longitude of the Earth is below that of the planet (before opposition in outer planets).

      • phase

        public float phase
        Visible phase percentage, from 0 to 1.

      • positionAngleOfAxis

        public double positionAngleOfAxis
        Position angle of axis in radians. 0 is towards north, 90 degrees towards East.

      • positionAngleOfPole

        public double positionAngleOfPole
        Position angle of pole in radians. Positive values means that the north hemisphere of the planet is towards the observer. For the Moon it will be the libration in latitude. As a general rule, this value is corrected from planetocentric to planetogeodetic, which means that in practice it is a sub-observer latitude that can be compared with topographic maps. Target class contains methods for transforming between both values.

      • longitudeOfCentralMeridian

        public double longitudeOfCentralMeridian
        Longitude of central meridian in radians. For giant planets (Jupiter, Saturn, Uranus, and Neptune) the value will be refered to system III of coordinates. For the Moon it will be the libration in longitude. The longitude is measured towards east for the Moon (positive values represents positions towards east or to the right on the Moon), the Sun, and the inner planets Mercury and Venus. For Mars and the rest of the outer planets this value is measured towards west (west longitudes are positive).

      • longitudeOfCentralMeridianSystemI

        public double longitudeOfCentralMeridianSystemI
        Longitude of central meridian in radians for system I of coordinates (mean rotation of equatorial belt). Only available in Jupiter and Saturn.

      • longitudeOfCentralMeridianSystemII

        public double longitudeOfCentralMeridianSystemII
        Longitude of central meridian in radians for system II of coordinates (mean rotation of the tropical belt). Only available in Jupiter, otherwise NULL.

      • longitudeOfCentralMeridianSystemIII

        public double longitudeOfCentralMeridianSystemIII
        Longitude of central meridian in radians for system III of coordinates (rotation of magnetic field). Only available in giant planets (Jupiter, Saturn, Uranus, and Neptune).

      • brightLimbAngle

        public float brightLimbAngle
        Bright limb angle in radians.

      • subsolarLatitude

        public double subsolarLatitude
        Subsolar latitude. In case of Saturn, Uranus, and Neptune, can be considered the ring plane ilumination angle. It depends on the relative position of the Sun. As a general rule, this value is corrected from planetocentric to planetogeodetic, which means that in practice it is a sub-observer latitude that can be compared with topographic maps. Target class contains methods for transforming between both values.

      • subsolarLongitude

        public double subsolarLongitude
        Subsolar longitude. It depends on the relative position of the Sun. In giant planets the value is refered to System III of coordinates.

      • paralacticAngle

        public float paralacticAngle
        Paralactic angle in radians.

      • azimuth

        public double azimuth
        Azimuth in radians. It is 0 for an object towards South, and -90 degrees if it is towards East.

      • elevation

        public double elevation
        Geometric/apparent elevation in radians. For apparent ephemerides the apparent elevation will be provided, unless the elevation itself is below -2 degrees. In this case the elevation will be geometric.

      • heliocentricEclipticLongitude

        public double heliocentricEclipticLongitude
        Mean heliocentric ecliptic longitude in radians for the output equinox and frame defined in the ephemeris object. For JPL ephemerides the value returned is heliocentric, for the others it is in fact barycentric (referred to solar system barycenter). As with other ephemerides values, this value is referred to the time the source emitted the light that reaches the observer (it is corrected for light-time), not to the input time of the ephemerides.

      • heliocentricEclipticLatitude

        public double heliocentricEclipticLatitude
        Mean heliocentric ecliptic latitude in radians for the output equinox and frame defined in the ephemeris object. For JPL ephemerides the value returned is heliocentric, for the others it is in fact barycentric (referred to solar system barycenter). As with other ephemerides values, this value is referred to the time the source emitted the light that reaches the observer (it is corrected for light-time), not to the input time of the ephemerides.

      • northPoleRA

        public double northPoleRA
        Right ascension of the north pole of rotation.

      • northPoleDEC

        public double northPoleDEC
        Declination of the north pole of rotation.

      • defectOfIllumination

        public float defectOfIllumination
        Defect of ilumination in radians.

      • rise

        public double[] rise
        Rise time/s as a Julian day in local time. By default if the object is above the horizon, then the value will be refered to the current day, otherwise it will be the next rise event in time. In case the object will not rise for the calculate date (from 0 to 24h local time of the observer), set time will be equal to RiseSetTransit.ALWAYS_BELOW_HORIZON.

      • set

        public double[] set
        Set time/s as a Julian day in local time. By default if the object is above the horizon, then the value will be refered to the current day, otherwise it will be the next set event in time. In case the object will not set for the calculate date (from 0 to 24h local time of the observer), set time will be equal to RiseSetTransit.ALWAYS_BELOW_HORIZON.

      • transit

        public double[] transit
        Transit (usually maximum elevation) time/s as a Julian day in local time. By default if the object is above the horizon, then the value will be refered to the current day, otherwise it will be the next transit event in time.

      • transitElevation

        public float[] transitElevation
        Transit geometric/apparent elevation/s from horizon in radians. Usually maximum elevation, but not necessarily.

      • constellation

        public java.lang.String constellation
        Constellation where the object is located.

      • surfaceBrightness

        public float surfaceBrightness
        Surface brightness if mag/arcsecond^2, or 0 if the object is a point source or has no clear angular size.

      • lightTime

        public float lightTime
        Holds light time from observer to object in days.

      • name

        public java.lang.String name
        Name of the body.

      • status

        public java.lang.String status
        Holds additional information for this object, for example if it is eclipsed in case it represents the ephemerides of a natural or artificial satellites, or if is occulted.
